    thinking: "**Designing the Visualizer Component**\n\nI\'ve decided on the component location: `/src/components/VascularVisualizer.tsx`. Now, my focus shifts to designing a dynamic 3D and 2D canvas simulation. This interactive visualizer will be a core feature, and I\'m keen to make it really sophisticated.\n\n\n**Refining the Interaction Design**\n\nI\'m now diving deep into making the visualizer component truly engaging. My goal is to craft an interactive Isometric Vascular Stem Cross-Section within `/src/components/VascularVisualizer.tsx`. I envision a canvas (or potentially an SVG + canvas blend) where each layer responds to user interaction. Hovering or clicking should highlight and reveal crucial information, with a modern aesthetic across the board. The layering concept is refined with outer epidermis, inner cortex, a vascular cambium, phloem and xylem layers, and a central pith core, each with specific visual properties and interactive behavior.\n\n\n**Visualizing the Fluid Dynamics**\n\nI\'m now implementing the detailed longitudinal schematic view for specific processes. When focusing on \"transpiration\" or \"translocation\", the visualizer will zoom in, showcasing the xylem, phloem, and companion cells with glowing particle simulations. I\'m focusing on the glowing particles to simulate water conduction (neon-blue) and sugar translocation (golden), whose speed is controlled by sliders. I am also working on an osmosis bridge to illustrate the Munch Pressure-Flow Hypothesis! Finally, I am looking at adding an evaporation/steam effect.\n\n\n**Simulating the Vapor Effect**\n\nI\'ve got the transpiration visual effects figured out! As water particles reach the stomata, they burst into a beautiful misty vapor effect. I\'m also visualizing turgor pressure as a glowing fluid background in the phloem, whose intensity is now synchronized with the sugar loading slider. To make the canvas even better, I am using gradients, shadow blurs, and fading trail effects. I am also working on touch and mouse interactions to rotate the isometric stem cross-section, or trigger a \"Sugar Pulse\" by clicking on the Source/Sink! I am now considering how the day/night cycle affects the visualizer. I am considering having Day Mode be clean parchment.\n\n\n**Implementing the Visual Themes**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the day and night visual themes. The \"Day Mode\" will be a clean parchment or high-contrast slate light theme with warm lighting. On the other hand, the \"Night Mode\" will be an immersive deep-space cinematic dark theme. I\'m visualizing glowing neon pathways. I am setting the water particles to glow electric cyan, sugar particles to glow rich golden-orange, and companion cells to pulse in violet, like a high-end bioluminescent plant visualization!\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI\'m starting to draft the component\'s state, including sliders for xylem and phloem rates, active hovered parts, interaction buttons, and zoom and rotation levels. I am making these smooth via Framer Motion or `requestAnimationFrame`. Finally, I\'m beginning the drawing code, targeting the 3D isometric stem and its detailed longitudinal view, for when `focus` is set to `\'stem\'`. I\'ll start by drawing concentric ellipses to build the stem cross-section.\n\n\n**Developing the Layer Structure**\n\nI\'m now detailing the component layout. The outermost epidermis layer will use a delicate green border or a dashed glass effect. Next, I\'ll build concentric rings for the cortex, phloem (with bundles), cambium, xylem, and the central pith. I\'m excited by rendering a 3D cylindrical wedge, sliced to reveal cross-sections and longitudinal views. My goal is to craft a premium animated sliced stem wedge that is unique. I am writing the canvas drawing algorithm to achieve this! The final interaction logic will depend on the currently active `focus`.\n\n\n**Refining the Animation Logic**\n\nI am now focusing on the camera\'s animation. I\'ll utilize `useRef` and `useEffect` to manage the canvas and animation loop, which will smoothly interpolate the camera\'s zoom, rotation, and slide based on the active focus mode. For the stem view, I\'m setting target values for zoom, center, and rotation. Xylem and phloem views will have their own distinct camera configurations. Furthermore, if the focus is \'comparison\', I will render two side-by-side columns with simulated osmosis between them.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create `/src/components/VascularVisualizer.tsx`. It implements a cinematic, high-performance HTML5 Canvas rendering engine. It handles:\n1. **Cinematic Smooth Camera Transitions (Lerp)**: Smoothly flies, zooms, and rotates the camera between the 3D stem cross-section and close-up views of xylem and phloem based on the active story step.\n2. **Interactive 3D Isometric Stem**: A beautifully styled, rotating 3D plant stem cylinder with a wedge sliced open to reveal internal vascular layers (Cortex, Phloem, Cambium, Xylem, and Pith) with interactive hover detection.\n3. **Dual Particle Transport Simulation**:\n   - **Xylem (Water)**: Glowing electric-blue particles rising, illustrating root pressure, cohesion, adhesion, and vaporizing into transpiration mist at leaf stomata.\n   - **Phloem (Sucrose)**: Glowing golden sucrose particles loaded by Companion Cells, showing mass flow pressure gradients.\n   - **Osmotic Recycling**: Solute-potential-driven water molecules bridging the xylem and phloem.\n4. **Day/Night Lighting System**: Translates from a clean, warm parchment-style day mode to a gorgeous bioluminescent sci-fi dark-mode.\n5. **Interactive Controls**: Let users adjust transpiration rates and sucrose loading in real-time, instantly shifting flow rates and particle dynamics. Let\'s write the code now."
