    thinking: "**Enumerating Core Components**\n\nI\'ve got the initial core components mapped out: types, data structures, a VascularVisualizer, and a DiagnosticQuiz. Now, I\'m shifting my focus to encompass the application as a whole, specifically, the various cells existing within. I\'m noting the Xylem\'s vessels, tracheids, parenchyma, and fibres, and the Phloem\'s sieve components.\n\n\n**Constructing Cell Explorer**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in developing the Cell Explorer Component! I\'ve decided to build a `/src/components/CellExplorer.tsx` file for the core of the Cell Explorer. I\'m focusing on its key features: the Xylem/Phloem toggle, the cell grid display, and the clean glassmorphic card design for each cell. I\'m especially excited about the high-fidelity overlay with detailed physiological data and the interactive 3D-like SVG illustrations for each cell type: Vessels, Tracheids, Parenchyma, Fibres, and Sieve Components.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create `/src/components/CellExplorer.tsx` to build the Interactive Cellular Atlas.\nFeatures:\n1. **Glassmorphic Deck**: Displays the 4 xylem and 4 phloem cells using responsive grid card structures.\n2. **Interactive Cell Anatomy Graphics**: Each card expands to show an educational deep-dive accompanied by a custom, gorgeous vector illustration modeling the cell\'s precise biology (e.g. perforated plates on vessel members, pits on tracheids, companion cell coupled with sieve pores).\n3. **Adaptive Physiological Stat Matrices**: Lists structural properties like cell state, wall reinforcement, and conduit types.\n4. **Sub-Type Filters**: Allows users to isolate \"All cells\", \"Living cells\", or \"Dead cells\" instantly with fluid transitions. Let\'s write the code."
